{{notability|date=December 2017}}
The '''Division of Select Agents and Toxins''' (DSAT) of the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] is responsible for the [[Select Agent Program]] and the Etiologic Agent Import Permit Program. They inspect the laboratories of more than 300 organizations approved to use and transfer [[select agents]], and put regulations in place to minimize risk in the use of these bacterial agents and toxins.<ref>https://www.cdc.gov/phpr/documents/dsat_fact_sheet.pdf</ref>

DSAT investigates incidents related to the laboratory use of select agents and toxins and refers cases to the [[FBI]] and [[United States Department of Health and Human Services|HHS Office of Inspector General]] when necessary.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://oig.hhs.gov/oei/reports/oei-04-15-00430.pdf}}</ref> 

They also review experiments that are deemed "restricted experiments" because of their increased risk.<ref>{{cite journal |last1=Smith |first1=Jacinta |last2=Gangadharan |first2=Denise |last3=Weyant |first3=Robbin |title=Review of Restricted Experiment Requests, Division of Select Agents and Toxins, Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, 2006-2013 |journal=Health Security |date=1 September 2015 |volume=13 |issue=5 |pages=307–316 |doi=10.1089/hs.2015.0021 |url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4582684/ |issn=2326-5094}}</ref>

Samuel S. Edwin became the director of the division in 2016.<ref>{{cite web|title=CDC Announces New Director of Division of Select Agents and Toxins -- Occupational Health & Safety|url=https://ohsonline.com/articles/2016/08/04/cdc-announces-new-director-of-division-of-select-agents-and-toxins.aspx|website=Occupational Health & Safety|language=en}}</ref> The office's 2016 budget was approximately $21.5 million. 

