The '''Galveston Orientation and Amnesia Test (GOAT)''' is a measure of attention and orientation, especially to see if a patient has recovered from [[post-traumatic amnesia]] (PTA) after a [[traumatic brain injury]].<ref name="ZaslerMD2007">{{cite book|author1=Nathan Zasler|author2=Douglas Katz, MD|author3=Ross D. Zafonte|title=Brain Injury Medicine: Principles and Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=yplFkKimNcYC&pg=PA289|year=2007|publisher=Demos Medical Publishing|isbn=978-1-888799-93-4|pages=289}}</ref> This was the first measure created to test post-traumatic amnesia, and is still the most widely used test.<ref name="ZaslerMD2007" /> The test was created by Harvey S. Levin and colleagues (1979), and features ten questions that assess temporal and spatial orientation, biographical recall, and memory.<ref name="DeLisaGans2005">{{cite book|author1=Joel A. DeLisa|author2=Bruce M. Gans|author3=Nicholas E. Walsh|title=Physical Medicine and Rehabilitation: Principles and Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=1sWk1GYCvKoC&pg=PA1012|year=2005|publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins|isbn=978-0-7817-4130-9|pages=1012–}}</ref> Points are awarded for responses to each question, with a 100 points possible. A score greater than 78 for three consecutive days is considered the threshold for emergence from post-traumatic amnesia.<ref name="MDMD2010">{{cite book|author1=David X. Cifu, MD|author2=Deborah Caruso, MD|title=Traumatic Brain Injury|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fLvA1tpCDLEC&pg=PA26|date=29 April 2010|publisher=Demos Medical Publishing|isbn=978-1-933864-61-7|pages=26}}</ref> This test is intended for patients aged 15 years or older. Younger patients are given a modified version of the test, known as the Children's Orientation and Attention Test (COAT).
The scores on this test have been found to relate to both the [[Glasgow Coma Scale]] and the [[Glasgow Outcome Scale]].<ref name="MapouSpector1995">{{cite book|author1=Robert L. Mapou|author2=Jack Spector|title=Clinical Neuropsychological Assessment: A Cognitive Approach|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Oc4MQr7NaDoC&pg=PA188|date=28 February 1995|publisher=Springer|isbn=978-0-306-44869-0|pages=188–}}</ref>
==Modified versions==
===MOAT=== A modified version of this test, known as MOAT or Modified GOAT, is a similar questionnaire that assesses memory, orientation, and attention. This modified version has multiple choice options for those who have [[Expressive language|expressive-language]] difficulties or who are intubated. Here, a score of greater than 60 for two consecutive days is considered emergence from PTA.<ref name="MDLew2013">{{cite book|author1=David X. Cifu, MD|author2=Henry L. Lew|title=Handbook of Polytrauma Care and Rehabilitation|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=teSdAAAAQBAJ&pg=PA224|date=10 September 2013|publisher=Demos Medical Publishing|isbn=978-1-936287-55-0|pages=224}}</ref>
===COAT=== The Children's Orientation and Attention Test (COAT) is a pediatric version of the test for ages 3–15.<ref name="MDMD2012">{{cite book|author1=Nathan D. Zasler MD|author2=Douglas I. Katz MD|author3=Ross D. Zafonte DO|author4=David B. Arciniegas MD |author5=M. Ross Bullock MD, PHD |author6=Jeffrey S. Kreutzer PHD, ABPP|title=Brain Injury Medicine, 2nd Edition: Principles and Practice|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=jF3OKmuHVBoC&pg=PA587|date=27 August 2012|publisher=Demos Medical Publishing|isbn=978-1-61705-057-2|pages=587}}</ref> This test assesses orientation by asking the child or adolescent to give their first and last names, their parents' names, and to identify their current location.<ref name="PhD2010">{{cite book|author=Andrew S. Davis PhD|title=Handbook of Pediatric Neuropsychology|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SU9-LSh4HgcC&pg=PT613|date=25 October 2010|publisher=Springer Publishing Company|isbn=978-0-8261-5737-9|pages=613}}</ref>
