The '''illegal drug trade in Panama''' includes trans-shipment of [[cocaine]] to the United States. The 1989 [[United States invasion of Panama]] to topple Dictator [[Manuel Noriega]] was justified in part by the need to combat [[drug trafficking]]. Noriega, the dictator of [[Panama]] from 1983 to 1989, had a relationship with the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) from the 1950s. More recently, Mexican cartels such as [[Sinaloa]] have been active in Panama.<ref name=stratfor>"The Sinaloa cartel, which STRATFOR believes is the most capable Mexican trafficker of cocaine, has been detected operating a fairly extensive overland smuggling route from Panama to El Salvador." - Stratfor, 26 March 2009, [http://www.stratfor.com/weekly/20090326_central_america_emerging_role_drug_trade Central America: An Emerging Role in the Drug Trade]</ref>
==Manuel Noriega== {{main|Manuel Noriega}}
Although the relationship did not become contractual until 1967, Noriega worked with the U.S. [[Central Intelligence Agency]] (CIA) from the late 1950s until the 1980s.<ref>{{cite news|title=Key dates for ex-Panama dictator Manuel Noriega |url=https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hms3CjNLe-a1Y-XsKUmUjnc22tCQD9FBCHN80 |agency=Associated Press |date=April 27, 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100430054945/https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5hms3CjNLe-a1Y-XsKUmUjnc22tCQD9FBCHN80 |archivedate=April 30, 2010 }}</ref> In 1988 the U.S. [[Drug Enforcement Administration]] indicted him on federal drug charges.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dea.gov/pubs/history/1985-1990.html |title=1985–1990 |work=DEA History Book |publisher=Drug Enforcement Administration |accessdate=December 23, 2008 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rH5xvq3Y?url=http://www.justice.gov/dea/pubs/history/1985-1990.html |archivedate=July 16, 2010 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/02/06/world/noriega-indicted-by-us-for-links-to-illegal-drugs.html?pagewanted=1 |work=The New York Times |title=Noriega Indicted By U.S. For Links To Illegal Drugs |first=Philip |last=Shenon |date=February 6, 1988 |accessdate=July 16, 2010 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5rH6770ys?url=http://www.nytimes.com/1988/02/06/world/noriega-indicted-by-us-for-links-to-illegal-drugs.html?pagewanted=1 |archivedate=July 16, 2010 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
The 1988 Senate Subcommittee on Terrorism, Narcotics and International Operations concluded that "The saga of Panama's General Manuel Antonio Noriega represents one of the most serious foreign policy failures for the United States. Throughout the 1970s and the 1980s, Noriega was able to manipulate U.S. policy toward his country, while skillfully accumulating near-absolute power in Panama. It is clear that each U.S. government agency which had a relationship with Noriega turned a blind eye to his corruption and drug dealing, even as he was emerging as a key player on behalf of the [[Medellín Cartel]] (a member of which was notorious Colombian drug lord [[Pablo Escobar]])." Noriega was allowed to establish "the hemisphere's first '[[Kleptocracy|narcokleptocracy]]'".<ref>{{cite journal |url=http://www.gwu.edu/~nsarchiv/NSAEBB/NSAEBB113/north06.pdf |title=Drugs, Law Enforcement and Foreign Policy |publisher=[[United States Government Printing Office]] |date=December 1988 |page=3 |format=[[PDF]]}}</ref>
One of the large financial institutions that he was able to use to launder money was the [[Bank of Credit and Commerce International]] (BCCI) which was shut down at the end of the Cold War by the FBI. Noriega shared his cell with ex-BCCI executives in the facility that is known as "Club Med".
As a result of the 1989 [[United States invasion of Panama|invasion of Panama]] by the United States, [[Manuel Noriega]] was removed from power, captured, detained as a [[prisoner of war]], and flown to the United States. Noriega was [[Trial|tried]] on eight counts of [[Illegal drug trade|drug trafficking]], [[Racket (crime)|racketeering]], and [[money laundering]] in April 1992. Noriega's U.S. prison sentence ended in September 2007;<ref name="XFman">{{cite news |title=Extradition fight halts former Panamanian leader Manuel Noriega's release from US prison |url=http://www.iht.com/articles/ap/2007/09/09/america/NA-GEN-US-Noriegas-Release.php |agency=Associated Press|work=[[International Herald Tribune]] |date=9 September 2007}}</ref> pending the outcome of [[extradition]] requests by both Panama and France, for [[trial in absentia|convictions ''in absentia'']] for murder in 1995 and money laundering in 1999, respectively. France was granted its extradition request in April 2010. He arrived in [[Paris]] on April 27, 2010,<ref>{{cite news |title=Noriega extradition to France angers abuse victims |date=27 April 2010 |accessdate=27 April 2010 |first=Juan |last=Zamorano |publisher=[[The Associated Press]] via ''[[The Washington Post]]'' |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2010/04/27/AR2010042703961.html}}</ref> and after a re-trial as a condition of the extradition, he was found guilty and sentenced to seven years in jail in July 2010.<ref name=AP_2010>{{cite news | url = https://www.google.com/hostednews/ap/article/ALeqM5iwFop1-UsXGNbhYRru5SpS57HWzwD9GQ7D0G0 | title = French court hands Noriega 7-year prison term | publisher = The Associated Press | date = July 7, 2010 }}</ref>
